<div class="smallprint">
<b>READER'S KEY — HOW THIS DOCUMENT IS PRODUCED</b><br>
This briefing is generated automatically by a fixed pipeline. This key is static boilerplate: it is never written or altered by the AI model and is identical in every edition.<br>
<b>Pipeline.</b> Posts are collected from a configured list of Telegram channels, then each post is analysed individually by a language model, which assigns it a headline, summary, category, threat level, named entities, and four 1–5 scores (importance, urgency, credibility, relevance). Posts are then scored, de-duplicated, ranked, and laid out into this document by deterministic code. The Intelligence Assessment front page is a separate model pass that synthesises the day's top reports into themes, signals, and actors, with trend data drawn from the preceding seven days.<br>
<b>Document order.</b> (1) <i>Intelligence Assessment</i> — situation summary, key themes, signals &amp; warnings, named actors, and emerging actors/topics (entities seen today but absent from the prior seven days). (2) <i>Lead Reports</i> — the day's most important stories in full detail (summary, entities, corroboration, images): every CRITICAL-rated item regardless of score, topped up with the highest-scored remaining reports to at least ten. (3) <i>Other Developments</i> — the remaining reports that cleared the priority threshold, each with headline, summary, and corroborating channels, in descending score order. (4) <i>In Brief</i> — lower-priority items, also in score order. (5) <i>Statistics</i> — the day's pipeline counts. Each story appears in exactly one section.<br>
<b>Scoring.</b> Each report's composite score = 0.4×importance + 0.3×urgency + 0.2×credibility + 0.1×relevance (each 1–5, model-assigned), multiplied by per-channel priority and credibility weights set in configuration. Configured keywords add a fixed boost; items categorised as Rumor are down-weighted; the threat badge nudges the rank (CRITICAL up, LOW down); older posts decay exponentially with age toward a floor, so they are demoted but never hidden. Reports confirmed by other channels receive a corroboration boost. Displayed scores are capped at 5.0. Reports scoring at least {{ "%.1f"|format(content.min_composite_score) }} (the configured threshold for this edition) escape In Brief; if too few qualify, the highest-scoring remainder are promoted so the briefing never runs thin.<br>
<b>De-duplication.</b> Near-identical reports across channels are merged: the highest-scored version is shown and the others appear on it as "Corroborated by" links rather than as separate entries; in In Brief this is abbreviated to "+N corrob".<br>
<b>Threat levels.</b> <b><span style="color:#c0392b;">&#9632; CRITICAL</span></b> / <b><span style="color:#d35400;">&#9632; HIGH</span></b> / <b><span style="color:#b7950b;">&#9632; MODERATE</span></b> / <b><span style="color:#1e8449;">&#9632; LOW</span></b> are the model's assessment of immediate significance, independent of the composite score — a low-scoring CRITICAL item is still promoted to Lead Reports. A CRITICAL badge additionally requires substantiation: rumors and low-credibility claims are shown as HIGH.<br>
<b>How to read.</b> Skim the front page for the day's shape, read Lead Reports in full, then scan Other Developments and In Brief top-down — every section is sorted most-important-first. Every ↗ link opens the original Telegram post for verification. All times are UTC. All summaries, titles, scores, and threat levels are machine-generated from single-source social media posts and should be treated as leads, not confirmed reporting.
